library(lattice)
library(RODBC)
ch = odbcConnect('Hyne',uid='sa',pwd="password12")
mypanel = function(x,y,...) {
  panel.abline(c(0,1), col='grey70', lty=2)
  panel.xyplot(x,y,...)
}
X = sqlQuery(ch, "
             select
                m.flitchId, SWILogNumber,
               g.MOE [E.g], 
               g.Density [den.g], 
               m.swv [v.d], 
               h.[Density_kg/m3] [den.d], 
               h.[MOE.cltraw] [E.d], 
               m.pith, 
               m.wane, 
               X_MOE/1000. [E.d.chh],
               X_Dens [den.d.chh]
             from (select flitchId, max(pith) pith, max(wane) wane, avg(swv) swv from manualMeas group by flitchId) m left join HyneDryBoards h on h.flitchId=m.flitchId
             left join ecoustic g on m.flitchId=g.flitchId
             left join CHHBoards c on m.flitchId=c.flitchId
             left join (
                select flitchId, max(SWILogNumber) SWILogNumber 
                from boardEndImages i, barcode_image bi, boardEndBarcodes b 
                where flitchId is not null and i.id=bi.imageId and bi.barcodeId=b.id group by flitchId
             ) f on f.flitchId=m.flitchId
             where g.MOE>0 and g.MOE<>6.5 
             ")
X$pith_wane = paste("pith =",X$pith,"; wane =",X$wane)
X$E.d.hitman = X$v.d^2*X$den.d.chh/1e9
X$v.g = sqrt(X$E.g*1e9/X$den.g)
X$E.g.corrected = X$E.g
X$E.g.corrected[X$v.g>4000] = (X$v.g[X$v.g>4000]/2)^2*X$den.g[X$v.g>4000]/1e9
nrow(X)
## [1] 895

895 (of ~1200) boards with the requisite matched green and dry (LHG and manual) data.

The outliers in the dry Hyne v CHH density plots are probably due to mis-merges in the Hyne dataset. From here on use the CHH density, partly because I have more faith in the CHH merge, but also because there are only 80 boards in the manual measurement set missing from the CHH whereas there are 222 boards missing in the Hyne.

SWV

  1. ViScan (CHH) v Hitman v LHG (Hyne). LHG results waiting of SH. => Use hitman for SWV

Green v Dry MOE

xyplot(E.d ~ E.g, X, 
       group=pith_wane, 
       auto.key=TRUE, 
       panel=mypanel, 
       xlab="Green MOE (ecoustic) / [GPa]", 
       ylab="Dry MOE (Metriguard CLT) / [GPa]",
       aspect='iso')

Around 5% have a green MOE twice what would be expected given the dry MOE. Most of these 5% are pith boards (which should probably be kept out of a high MOE sort!)

Green v Dry SWV

xyplot(v.d ~ v.g, X, 
       xlab="Green SWV (ecoustic) / [m/s]", 
       ylab="Dry SWV (hitman) / [m/s]", 
       group=pith_wane, 
       auto.key=TRUE, 
       panel=mypanel,
       aspect='iso')

Waney boards appear to have less correlation between green and dry SWV. Why? Green density more variable in waney boards?

Cluster of high green SWV, low dry SWV probably due to picking harmonic instead of fundamental. Easily fixed by halving Green SWV and recomputing green MOE.

Using Green MOE as a surrogate for Dry MOE

ML has proposed using green board MOE instead of dry MOE to determine log quality. If we did this with the Hyne dataset, would green board MOE be sufficient to correctly classify logs? (I.e rank logs same as dry board MOE would).

L = sqlQuery(ch, "select * from logs l full join yardTrimmed y on l.SWILogNumber=y.SWILogNumber where l.SWILogNumber is not null and DateAndTime>'2014-08-31 00:00:00' order by l.SWILogNumber")
for (i in 1:nrow(L)) {
  ii=!is.na(X$SWILogNumber) & X$SWILogNumber==L[i,"SWILogNumber"]
  L[i,"nboards"]=sum(ii)
  L[i,"E.dyn.green"]=mean(X$E.g[ii],na.rm=TRUE)
  L[i,"E.dyn.green.corrected"]=mean(X$E.g.corrected[ii],na.rm=TRUE)
  L[i,"E.dyn.dry.chh"]=mean(X$E.d.chh[ii],na.rm=TRUE) # viscan + chh density
  L[i,"E.dyn.dry.man"]=mean(X$E.d.hitman[ii],na.rm=TRUE) # manual + chh density
  L[i,"E.sta.dry.hyn"]=mean(X$E.d[ii],na.rm=TRUE) # clt
  #L[i,"E.dyn.dry.hyn"]=mean(X$E.d.lhg[ii],na.rm=TRUE) # lhg + xry : waiting on SH re-running
  
}
pairs(L[,c("E.dyn.green","E.dyn.green.corrected","E.dyn.dry.chh","E.dyn.dry.man","E.sta.dry.hyn")],
      lower.panel=function(x, y, digits = 2, prefix = "", cex.cor, ...)
{
    usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
    par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
    ii=!is.na(x) & !is.na(y)
    r <- abs(cor(x[ii], y[ii]))
    txt <- format(c(r, 0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
    txt <- paste0(prefix, txt)
    if(missing(cex.cor)) cex.cor <- 0.8/strwidth(txt)
    text(0.5, 0.5, txt, cex = cex.cor * r)
}, main="Comparison of Log Average MOE based on Various Board MOE Measures")

par(mfcol=c(1,1))
plot(rank(L$E.dyn.green), rank(L$E.dyn.dry.chh))

In the Hyne dataset, without correcting for boards whose SWV is 2x what it should be, green and dry board MOE rank logs quite differently. E.g. green MOE puts log 195 in the top 10%, whereas dry puts it in the bottom 10%!

Outliers probably due to Hyne mis-merge.

Static MOE (Hyne CLT) greater than dynamic (CHH). Offset is better model than different slope.

Hitman and CHH density good estimator of Hyne CLT MOE. Signs of nonlinearity?

CHH ViScan SWV less than hitman SWV (using same density) by about 1000 m/s.
